<h2><strong>30.2 â€“ Gross Domestic Produce (GDP)</strong></h2>
<p>I understand this is an absolute basic metric to start our discussion, but we will start with it for the same reason. Many of you may be familiar with it; if yes, please feel free to skip this section. For those who are not familiar with â€˜GDPâ€™, let me tell you a quick story.</p>
<p>After my sisterâ€™s marriage in 2002, she moved to Coimbatore, Tamil Nadu. I was in my early 20â€™s, and Iâ€™d often make weekend trips to Coimbatore to visit her and spend a few days with her. My sister had a very interesting neighbour in Coimbatore, and she would often tell me stories about them. On one of my visits, I got to meet the neighbours as well.</p>
<p>The neighbourâ€™s house had three family members â€“ husband and wife, both in their mid 50â€™s and a teenage daughter. Husband managed a steel kitchenware shop, which sold household items like rice cooker, pots, and pans. His wife managed a small homemade papad and pickle business, and the teenage daughter taught classical dance to the neighbourhood kids.</p>
<p>All three members of the house had an economic output. Given my unnecessary curiosity, I remember trying to figure out how much money this family made. I donâ€™t remember the exact math, but I remember these numbers; I estimated that â€“</p>
<ul>
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul>
<li>The husband sold goods worth 2 to 2.5L lakhs per month.</li>
<li>The wife sold goods worth 25K every month.</li>
<li>The daughter charged 500 per month per kid and had ten students, which was 5K per month.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Give or take, this small and admirable familyâ€™s monthly income was anywhere between 2.3 to 2.8L per month or about 34L per year on a gross basis. This family had no other source of income. In other words, 34L was the total economic output of this family after accounting for all the products and services collectively sold by this family.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/M11-C29-MF-MacroEconomics-WEB.jpg"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9739" height="359" sizes="(max-width: 540px) 100vw, 540px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/M11-C29-MF-MacroEconomics-WEB-300x200.jpg" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/M11-C29-MF-MacroEconomics-WEB-300x200.jpg 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/M11-C29-MF-MacroEconomics-WEB.jpg 600w" width="540"/></a></p>
<p>In a sense, I think it is ok to conclude that the familyâ€™s Gross Domestic Produceâ€™ (GDP) was 34L per year. &nbsp;If you realized, GDP here represents the total value of the economic output of the family, which includes goods sold (kitchenware), products manufactured and sold (papad and pickle), and services offered (dance classes).</p>
<p>Now step aside and think about the country as a whole. The country has many factories, companies, services units of various kinds; all of these collectively has an economic output. The combined economic value of all these entities (operating within the geographic boundaries of the country) represents the GDP of the country. If the companies do well and thrive, then naturally, the GDP of the country increases.</p>
<p>Or in other words, a growing GDP is a healthy economic sign. We all want the GDP of the country to increase.</p>
<p>Have a look at the Indian GDP ranking â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-1_GDP-rank.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9744" height="199" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-1_GDP-rank-1024x340.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-1_GDP-rank-1024x340.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-1_GDP-rank-300x100.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-1_GDP-rank-768x255.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-1_GDP-rank-1536x510.png 1536w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-1_GDP-rank.png 1632w" width="600"/></a></p>
<p>Iâ€™ve got this from Wikipedia, where they have tabulated the 2020 GDP rank of countries as per various estimates (IMF, World Bank, and UN).</p>
<p>India ranks around 6<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;or 5<sup>th</sup>, and the GDP itself is pegged to 2.6 to 2.9 Trillion USD. Do recollect, the collective economic output of India is estimated between 2.6 â€“ 2.9 Trillion USD. We are just below China, Japan, UK, and Germany.</p>
<p>While it is great to know we are in the top 5 GDPs of the world, it is also important to understand how our GDP grows. After all, we want to be better than being in the top 5, and we want to get there as quickly as possible.</p>
<p>To measure the speed at which a countryâ€™s GDP is growing, we need a growth rate. The number is usually expressed in percentage terms. Hence, if the percentage is 5%, it implies that a countryâ€™s GDP grows at 5%.</p>
<p>The technique of estimating the GDP growth rate is beyond this discussionâ€™s scope; we wonâ€™t get into that today but will use the widely accepted number.</p>
<p>Now, when it comes to measuring the GDP growth, there are two terms you should familiarize yourself with â€“</p>
<ul>
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul>
<li>The nominal GDP growth rate</li>
<li>The real GDP growth rate</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Both these growth rates measure the speed at which the GDP grows; if you guessed right, these rates are the CAGR of the GDP. Do recollect; we have discussed CAGR several times in this module.</p>
<p>To put this in context, take a look at this new paper headlines â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-2_nominal.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9742" height="109" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-2_nominal-1024x186.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-2_nominal-1024x186.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-2_nominal-300x55.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-2_nominal-768x140.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-2_nominal.png 1133w" width="600"/></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The reference point here is the â€˜nominal growthâ€™ rate.</p>
<p>The nominal growth rate is the absolute growth rate. While it is ok to use the nominal growth rate, it may not be an accurate representation of ground realities.</p>
<p>Let me explain.</p>
<p>Think of it as investing Rs.100 in stock. At a 10% growth rate and five years, Rs.100 grows to Rs.161/-. But is the value of Rs.161/- in 5 years the same as Rs.161/- today? Wonâ€™t it be right? And we know it wonâ€™t be the same because inflation eats into the purchasing power of money on year on year basis.</p>
<p>Hence to get the most accurate representation, we need to adjust the growth rate to inflation. When we adjust the nominal GDP growth rate to inflation in GDP, we get the <strong>real GDP growth rate</strong>.</p>
<p>Real GDP growth = Nominal GDP growth â€“ Inflation.</p>
<p>Assuming the inflation at around 4.5% (ranges between 4.5% to 5%), real GDP of India â€“</p>
<p>10% â€“ 4.5%</p>
<p>= 5.5%</p>
<p>Do take a look at this snapshot; it estimates the real GDP growth at 5% â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-3_real-GDP.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9737" height="79" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-3_real-GDP.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-3_real-GDP.png 788w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-3_real-GDP-300x40.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-3_real-GDP-768x101.png 768w" width="600"/></a></p>
<p>The snapshot is from the Department of Economic Affairs; you can read the entire paper here â€“ <u><a href="https://dea.gov.in/sites/default/files/March%202020.pdf">https://dea.gov.in/sites/default/files/March%202020.pdf</a>.</u></p>
<p>I also found this interesting chart from the same paper; I thought Iâ€™d share it here for your quick reference â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-4_emde.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9743" height="362" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-4_emde.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-4_emde.png 682w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-4_emde-300x181.png 300w" width="600"/></a></p>
<p>Thanks to COVID, most of the economies (from the GDP perspective) took a hit in 2020. But they are all expected to bounce back up in 2021 and perhaps 2022. Whether this will pan out as per estimates or not is an unknown. But the stock markets at least seem to factor this ðŸ™‚</p>
<p>Anyway, at this point, I want you to take a break and think about this â€“</p>
<ul>
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
