<h2><strong>30.3 â€“ GDP and Market cap</strong></h2>
<p>We have discussed the concept of market cap earlier in Varsity. For those of you not familiar with market cap, here is a quick note â€“</p>
<p>Assume the stock price of a certain company is Rs.75/- per share. Further, assume that the company has only 1000 shares outstanding of this company.</p>
<p>The market cap of this company is â€“</p>
<p>Stock price x total outstanding shares</p>
<p>= 75 x 1000</p>
<p>= Rs.75,000/-</p>
<p>The total outstanding shares of this company are constant, but the stock price fluctuates daily. The higher the stock price, the higher is the market cap and vice versa.</p>
<p>Now assume another company has 2000 shares outstanding, and the stock price is 105 per share. The market cap of this company is â€“</p>
<p>= 105 x 2000</p>
<p>=2,10,000/-</p>
<p>Now assume (the last assumption, I promise) that the entire market comprises just these two companies. The entire market cap of this market is â€“</p>
<p>75000 + 210000</p>
<p>=2,85,000/-</p>
<p>Hopefully, with this arbitrary example, you got a sense of the concept of â€˜market cap of the marketâ€™. The market cap of Indian companies (sum of the market cap of all the listed companies in the country) as of Jan 2021 is roughly $2.5 Trillion.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-5_mkt-cap.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9741" height="116" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-5_mkt-cap.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-5_mkt-cap.png 678w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-5_mkt-cap-300x58.png 300w" width="600"/></a></p>
<p>One of the direct established correlations is that as the countryâ€™s GDP improves, so will the market cap. If the market cap does well, then equity investments are bound to well. We have seen this happen in the past.</p>
<p>So when you look at the GDP data, think about how the country is placed in terms of GDP, and it is expected to do over the next 5 or 10 years.</p>
<p>For instance, here is a thought about the Indian GDP situation â€“</p>
<ul>
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul>
<li>India is a 2.6 Trillion USD GDP as of 2021</li>
<li>The real GDP growth rate is 5.5%</li>
<li>The countries above us in the GDP rank, i.e. Japan, Germany, and the UK, have large GDPs, but their real growth rates are lower.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Even if India did nothing spectacular or did nothing stupid to degrow, then under a decent real GDP growth rate (and slow down in developed countries), the GDP rank is bound to increase.</p>
<p>No think about a growing GDP plus the largest democracy globally, and top it up with a large working population; what do you expect?</p>
<p>Well, these are factors usually is a precursor to attracting more investment capital into the country. With these investments coming in, corporates are expected to do well, and in turn, the countryâ€™s market cap is expected to do well.</p>
<p>Will this happen overnight? No.</p>
<p>Will this happen over the next 1-2 years? Maybe not.</p>
<p>Will this happen over the next 8-10 years? Well, it seems likely.</p>
<p>Hence, the need to stay invested for a longer-term.</p>
<h2><strong>30.4 â€“ India Inc </strong></h2>
<p>Think about a corporate entity. A corporate entity or a company usually has few sources of revenue and a set of expenses. The difference between the revenue and expense, if positive, results in a profit to the company. If the difference between the revenue and expense is negative, then that is a loss to the company.</p>
<p>Now think about India as a company. The companyâ€™s management is the Government, which is democratically elected. The company has a few revenue sources, mainly in terms of taxes, and the company also has expenses mainly in terms of capital and revenue expenses. If the income minus expense is positive, thatâ€™s a surplus to the country, else a deficit.</p>
<p>Take a look at the snapshot below; Iâ€™ve got this from the website of Controller General of Accounts; here is the link â€“</p>
<p>http://www.cga.nic.in/GlanceReport/Published/2018-2019.aspx</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-6_India-finance.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9736" height="439" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 501px) 100vw, 501px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-6_India-finance.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-6_India-finance.png 774w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-6_India-finance-300x263.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-6_India-finance-768x673.png 768w" width="501"/></a></p>
<p>The data you see above is for the Financial Year 2018-19, represented in Rupee Crores. Let us break this down to understand the numbers better.</p>
<p>The first line here details India Incâ€™s Revenue; it is called the â€˜Revenue Receiptsâ€™. These receipts act as the sources of revenue for the Government. There are two broad categories of revenue for the Government, i.e. Taxes and Non-tax revenue.</p>
<p><strong>Taxes Revenue </strong>â€“ Tax revenue includes all sorts of taxes that the Government collects. Broadly, taxes can be classified as â€˜Direct Taxesâ€™ and â€˜Indirect Taxesâ€™. The direct taxes include taxes paid by individuals, called the â€˜Personal Income taxesâ€™ and the corporatesâ€™ taxes, called the â€˜Corporate Income taxâ€™.</p>
<p>Indirect taxes mainly include the tax in the form of â€˜GSTâ€™.</p>
<p>As you can see, India Inc collected close to 14.8L Crore as taxes in 2018-19; this includes both direct and indirect taxes.</p>
<p>Remember, when GST is charged, a portion goes to the state and a portion to the centre. Hence when you look at 14.8LCr, this is the â€˜net to the centreâ€™, which means that the actual tax collection is higher than 14.8L Cr. Of course, you can get the exact value by inspecting this report further, but Iâ€™ll refrain from doing so. But if I remember right, roughly 2/3<sup>rd</sup>&nbsp;is retained by the centre, 1/3 is distributed to states.</p>
<p><strong>Non-tax revenue â€“ </strong>Apart from the tax revenue, the Government has a â€˜non-tax revenueâ€™ as an income source. The non-tax revenue source mainly includes the dividends paid out by the PSU companies (companies like LIC, NTPCL, ONGC, NALCO etc.), where the Government of India is a majority stakeholder. Apart from dividend income, the Government also has revenue by selling stakes in these companies, often referred to as the disinvestment program. The non-tax revenue for 2018-19 was roughly 2.4L Cr.</p>
<p>Total revenue is the sum of these two revenue lines, which is roughly 18.2L Cr.</p>
<p>The Government has expenses, and these expenses can be categorized into two buckets, i.e. the â€˜Revenue Expenditureâ€™ and â€˜Capital Expenditure.</p>
<p><strong>Revenue Expenditure</strong> â€“ These expenditures include subsidies across various Government schemes, salaries to Govt employees, interest payments etc. The revenue expenditure is a big bill that the Govt has to pay, and as we can see from the snapshot, this bill stood at 21.4L.</p>
<p><strong>Capital Expenditure</strong>&nbsp;â€“ The capital expenditure, on the other hand, is the Governmentâ€™s expenditure on infrastructure; this includes things like roads, bridges, hospitals, electrical grids, transportation etc. The capital expenditure is 3.1L Crore.</p>
<p>Think about it, capital expenditure is 3.1L Cr, while the revenue expenditure is nearly seven times more at 21L Cr. If the Govt were to spend more on Capital expenditure, it leads to better infrastructure, spurs business growth, creates jobs, and leads to better tax collection.</p>
<p>As a long-term investor, you need to keep track of trends in these spend patterns and get a sense of how the country is evolving.</p>
<p>The sum of revenue and capital expenditure is the total expenditure of the Govt, which is roughly 24.57Cr.</p>
<p>So, on the one hand, Govt collected revenue of 18.2L Cr, and on the other hand, the expenses stood at 24.57Cr. The expenses are much higher than the income. The negative difference, i.e. to the extent of nearly 6.3L Cr, is called the â€˜<strong>Fiscal Deficit</strong>â€™.</p>
<p>From the same report, Iâ€™ve pulled the GDP data â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-7_gdp-data.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9738" height="336" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 538px) 100vw, 538px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-7_gdp-data.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-7_gdp-data.png 691w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-7_gdp-data-300x188.png 300w" width="538"/></a></p>
<p>The countryâ€™s GDP as per 2018-19 data is 190.1L Crore. If you calculate the Fiscal Deficit as a percentage of GDP â€“</p>
<p>6.3L Cr / 190.1L Cr</p>
<p>= 3.3%</p>
<p>Any macroeconomic debate or discussion, this is the ratio that gets spoken about the most. The Government puts in massive efforts to contain the Fiscal Deficit to GDP ratio to sub 4%.</p>
<p>To put this in perspective, do check this extract from Wikipedia â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-8_US-fiscal.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-9740" height="53" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-8_US-fiscal-1024x90.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-8_US-fiscal-1024x90.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-8_US-fiscal-300x26.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-8_US-fiscal-768x67.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Image-8_US-fiscal.png 1129w" width="600"/></a></p>
<p>The USâ€™s fiscal deficit as a percentage of GDP is nearly 4.7%, which is quite staggering.</p>
<p>While at it, we can crunch one more data point, i.e. <strong>net tax collected as a percentage of GDP</strong>&nbsp;â€“</p>
<p>= 17.3/190.1</p>
<p>= 9.1%</p>
<p>If we include the share of stateâ€™s, this ratio is roughly at 11-12%. Tax collection as a percentage of GDP is an important metric; remember, the higher the tax collection, the higher is the revenue, which means the probability of shrinking the fiscal deficit is higher.</p>
<p>So what will lead to higher tax collection? Things like newer job creation, business expansion, improvement in ease of doing business, greater compliance, etc., result in higher tax collection.</p>
<p>Again, to remind you, you need to track these numbers to understand how the country operates. Remember, when you invest in the long term, your fortunes depend on how your investments perform, depending on how India as a country performs.</p>
<p>Without a sense of these basic details, it is equivalent to investing in the dark.</p>
<p>Iâ€™ll end this discussion here; as you can imagine, the topic is vast, and we have only scratched the surface ðŸ™‚</p>
