<h3><strong>Key takeaways from this chapter </strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>The countryâ€™s GDP represents the countryâ€™s collective economic output; this includes all the goods and services produced within the countryâ€™s geographic boundary.</li>
<li>The nominal GDP growth rate is the GDPâ€™s absolute growth rate; it does not adjust for inflation.</li>
<li>The real GDP growth rate adjusts for inflation.</li>
<li>With 2.6 to 2.9 Trillion USD, Indiaâ€™s GDP stands at 5<sup>th</sup>/6<sup>th</sup>position in the global GDP rank.</li>
<li>As the GDP of the country expands, the market cap also tends to expand.</li>
<li>India Incâ€™s revenue consists of tax and non-tax revenue.</li>
<li>India, Incâ€™s expense consists of revenue and capital expenditure.</li>
</ul>
